The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Friday, April 02, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Krishnagar, April 1: A hospital here refused to hand over a two-and-a-half-year-old girl to a man who claimed to be her father.				 																																	Little Jaya was admitted to Jawaharlal Nehru Memorial Hospital in Kalyani three days ago. Residents hospitalised her on Monday night after she and her escort were hit by a vehicle on NH 34 near Chakdah. The childs escort was brought dead to the emergency ward, said Nirupam Biswas, the hospital superintendent. Ranjit Burman, 30, came to the hospital today and said Jaya was her daughter but could not provide a proof. Jaya could not recognise her father. The hospital has asked Burman to return with some concrete evidence.				 																																	Tehatta: Ghanashyam Roy, who was under trial for torturing his wife and on bail, allegedly hanged himself at his Palashipara home on Wednesday night. Roy owns a market complex in Tehatta. He was arrested a month ago along with his mother, brothers and sisters for allegedly torturing his wife. They were released last week on bail after remaining under judicial custody for a fortnight. Police said Roy was being repeatedly accused by his family members for their arrests.				 																																	Durgapur: Three youths drowned in the Damodar near Ranigunj on Thursday afternoon. They were in a group of eight picnickers. Srikant Joshi, 20, Surinder Singh, 21, and Anup Sukla, 20, were all students of the local TDB College. Their bodies were recovered in the evening.				 																																	Calcutta: Former footballer Shyam Thapa is being considered as the BJPs candidate for the Darjeeling Lok Sabha seat. State party president Tathagata Roy confirmed on Thursday that Thapa was one of the contenders. A final decision would be taken by the weekend.
